166
00:08:11,603 --> 00:08:13,925
and put the story in the players' hands.

167
00:08:13,925 --> 00:08:16,047
And this is really important because

168
00:08:16,047 --> 00:08:18,709
this story is about trying to balance your career with your family.

169
00:08:18,709 --> 00:08:20,570
And that's a really big question.

170
00:08:20,570 --> 00:08:21,831
What are the right answers there?

171
00:08:21,831 --> 00:08:24,133
And I'd be lying if I said I knew what was important.

172
00:08:24,133 --> 00:08:24,213
So...

173
00:08:24,894 --> 00:08:28,115
My goal wasn't for the game to be a platform for my own beliefs.

174
00:08:28,115 --> 00:08:30,417
Instead, my goal was to make it a question game,

175
00:08:30,417 --> 00:08:32,498
not a message game.

176
00:08:32,498 --> 00:08:33,278
The player doesn't give,

177
00:08:33,278 --> 00:08:35,940
or the game doesn't give the player a specific goal

178
00:08:35,940 --> 00:08:37,841
or judge whether the decisions are right or wrong.

179
00:08:37,841 --> 00:08:40,282
It just lets the player make choices

180
00:08:40,282 --> 00:08:42,143
and try to give them reasonable consequences

181
00:08:42,143 --> 00:08:44,224
and kind of feedback the effects of their decisions.

182
00:08:44,224 --> 00:08:48,347
So what I really wanted to do was create a dynamic narrative,

183
00:08:48,347 --> 00:08:49,948
not necessarily a branching plot.

184
00:08:49,948 --> 00:08:51,128
I wanted to create a narrative

185
00:08:51,128 --> 00:08:53,390
that was based solely on the player's input.

186
00:08:53,770 --> 00:08:58,215
As opposed to a branching plot where every player has the same series of events and choices.

187
00:08:58,215 --> 00:09:03,421
So, I think it'd be useful to quickly establish what I mean by a branching plot.

188
00:09:03,421 --> 00:09:05,444
A branching plot is created by a writer or designer.

189
00:09:05,444 --> 00:09:11,791
And though the player does make some decisions, the events come in the same order every time.

190
00:09:11,791 --> 00:09:13,853
So, the plot starts moving along.

191
00:09:15,742 --> 00:09:18,324
And at some point, the player reaches a decision point.

192
00:09:18,324 --> 00:09:19,484
And they're given multiple options.

193
00:09:19,484 --> 00:09:22,866
Maybe they have to choose between different missions,

194
00:09:22,866 --> 00:09:24,307
or align with one of two factions,

195
00:09:24,307 --> 00:09:26,388
or even decide if a character lives or dies.

196
00:09:26,388 --> 00:09:28,269
And this technique is used very frequently

197
00:09:28,269 --> 00:09:30,290
in games like Mass Effect or the Bioshock series.

198
00:09:30,290 --> 00:09:31,050
Very familiar.

199
00:09:31,050 --> 00:09:33,671
So the player decides what they want to do,

200
00:09:33,671 --> 00:09:35,953
and there are now two branches of the story.

201
00:09:35,953 --> 00:09:38,074
And these are both authored content

202
00:09:38,074 --> 00:09:39,394
that are based on that choice.

203
00:09:40,143 --> 00:09:42,025
And the player might be given another major decision

204
00:09:42,025 --> 00:09:43,085
along one of these branches.

205
00:09:43,085 --> 00:09:45,467
So they decide again, and the first choice

206
00:09:45,467 --> 00:09:48,389
might fold back into the branch coming from the new choice.

207
00:09:48,389 --> 00:09:50,731
But eventually things probably fold back together

208
00:09:50,731 --> 00:09:54,053
towards the end, and you're presented with one final decision

209
00:09:54,053 --> 00:09:59,056
that, once you choose there, it splits out

210
00:09:59,056 --> 00:10:00,717
to different endings for different players.

211
00:10:00,717 --> 00:10:01,998
And this is frequently done on a sort

212
00:10:01,998 --> 00:10:04,059
of good, neutral, or bad ending.

213
00:10:04,059 --> 00:10:05,520
That's not the case all the time,

214
00:10:05,520 --> 00:10:08,042
but it's a pretty common trope there.

215
00:10:08,615 --> 00:10:14,178
And before going on, I want to be clear that this is a perfectly valid structure for a game plot.

216
00:10:14,178 --> 00:10:16,519
I'm not, my talk is not a screed against this kind of plot.

217
00:10:16,519 --> 00:10:21,742
I wanted to do something differently, but these plots can obviously work very well in games

218
00:10:21,742 --> 00:10:26,265
and give players really memorable experiences where they make choices that are really powerful to them.

219
00:10:26,265 --> 00:10:30,267
So I just want to make sure that this doesn't come off as me trashing this kind of branching narrative,

220
00:10:30,267 --> 00:10:31,108
because I think it's fine.

221
00:10:31,928 --> 00:10:38,214
But in my game, I did want to impose as little pre-authored structure as possible from, from my angle.

222
00:10:38,214 --> 00:10:42,238
So instead of writing a story, and even a story with a bunch of choices,

223
00:10:42,238 --> 00:10:46,582
I instead wanted to create narrative systems from which a player-driven story would emerge.

224
00:10:46,582 --> 00:10:49,926
So actually a systems-based narrative.

225
00:10:49,926 --> 00:10:53,009
So I made a bunch of structural decisions to try to make this happen.

226
00:10:53,009 --> 00:10:56,052
And the first, and maybe most important one, is that

227
00:10:56,382 --> 00:10:58,903
the chapters in the game come in a random order on each playthrough.

228
00:10:58,903 --> 00:11:00,744
So I actually sort of burned the boats and

229
