00:11:43,736 --> 00:11:44,896
as the authorship of the game.

254
00:11:44,896 --> 00:11:47,357
I wanted to create something where the player has to make

255
00:11:47,357 --> 00:11:48,957
personal decisions to create this story.

256
00:11:48,957 --> 00:11:52,238
So I tried to take each chapter and make each of the

257
00:11:52,238 --> 00:11:54,939
decisions the player has to make equally sympathetic from

258
00:11:54,939 --> 00:11:56,459
the different perspectives in the game.

259
00:11:56,459 --> 00:11:58,680
I didn't want players to get to a chapter and say, oh, this

260
00:11:58,680 --> 00:12:00,881
is clearly the right answer, or this is the good versus

261
00:12:00,881 --> 00:12:03,281
evil answer, or obviously I should do this.

262
00:12:03,281 --> 00:12:05,722
I kind of wanted them to have to be sympathetic to all

263
00:12:05,722 --> 00:12:07,542
characters and have to say, wow, what do I really think is

264
00:12:07,542 --> 00:12:08,002
right here?

265
00:12:08,002 --> 00:12:09,263
What do I think is more important here?

266
00:12:09,643 --> 00:12:11,526
So, again, it's a question game, not a message game.

267
00:12:11,526 --> 00:12:15,631
And more specifically, it's a game about trying to balance

268
00:12:15,631 --> 00:12:18,315
your career and your dreams with your family.

269
00:12:18,315 --> 00:12:20,598
So all of your decisions are based on making choices

270
00:12:20,598 --> 00:12:23,101
that prioritize one of these things here.

271
00:12:23,101 --> 00:12:24,483
And the high concept is essentially...

272
00:12:25,353 --> 00:12:27,234
a game with nine chapters, each of which

273
00:12:27,234 --> 00:12:28,954
asks you to make a decision on these axes

274
00:12:28,954 --> 00:12:31,055
in a slightly different way.

275
00:12:31,055 --> 00:12:32,595
And the hope being that you'll end up

276
00:12:32,595 --> 00:12:35,717
with a set of relationships at the end of the game that

277
00:12:35,717 --> 00:12:37,377
reflects your own choices on that subject,

278
00:12:37,377 --> 00:12:39,718
and that the story is almost like a mirror to help you

279
00:12:39,718 --> 00:12:42,459
process your own values on this specific question.

280
00:12:44,057 --> 00:12:46,018
So I want to walk through an example chapter,

281
00:12:46,018 --> 00:12:48,059
just to make sure it's clear how the game works,

282
00:12:48,059 --> 00:12:50,821
so that we'll have a vocabulary going forward.

283
00:12:50,821 --> 00:12:52,902
In each chapter, you spend time sneaking around the house

284
00:12:52,902 --> 00:12:54,523
and trying to remain hidden.

285
00:12:54,523 --> 00:12:56,624
And so you read things the characters have written.

286
00:12:57,668 --> 00:12:59,891
You look at things that Tommy has drawn.

287
00:12:59,891 --> 00:13:01,832
You read the character's thoughts to see what they're

288
00:13:01,832 --> 00:13:02,413
thinking about.

289
00:13:02,413 --> 00:13:04,755
You even explore their memories and relive past

290
00:13:04,755 --> 00:13:06,497
conversations and past events.

291
00:13:06,497 --> 00:13:09,380
And all these things help you piece together what's going on

292
00:13:09,380 --> 00:13:10,100
in each chapter.

293
00:13:10,100 --> 00:13:12,383
So you have a discovery phase where you uncover

294
00:13:12,383 --> 00:13:13,263
this type of stuff.

295
00:13:13,263 --> 00:13:16,206
And each character has their own chain of clues.

296
00:13:16,206 --> 00:13:19,009
And so what you want to do is basically find enough clues

297
00:13:19,009 --> 00:13:21,992
for each character to discover how they want to resolve the

298
00:13:21,992 --> 00:13:23,013
dilemma in the chapter.

299
00:13:24,162 --> 00:13:27,205
So to use an example of a chapter called The Show,

300
00:13:27,205 --> 00:13:29,607
in this chapter, Linda is going to be putting on an art show

301
00:13:29,607 --> 00:13:29,947
in town.

302
00:13:29,947 --> 00:13:31,529
And she's really under the gun trying

303
00:13:31,529 --> 00:13:33,670
to finish a last piece before the art show goes live.

304
00:13:33,670 --> 00:13:37,354
And she's asked Dan to help her with some promo materials

305
00:13:37,354 --> 00:13:40,556
and also asked if he could help her find an agent.

306
00:13:41,800 --> 00:13:44,742
But meanwhile, Dan is behind on his own deadline.

307
00:13:44,742 --> 00:13:46,583
His agent's writing him, he's dodging phone calls,

308
00:13:46,583 --> 00:13:48,204
and he's got a big deadline due Monday,

309
00:13:48,204 --> 00:13:50,466
and he's super under the gun himself

310
00:13:50,466 --> 00:13:52,467
and doesn't have the time to do it.

311
00:13:52,467 --> 00:13:54,449
And finally, to make matters worse,

312
00:13:54,449 --> 00:13:56,050
he had also promised their son Tommy

313
00:13:56,050 --> 00:13:57,431
that they were gonna go to the beach that day

314
00:13:57,431 --> 00:13:58,372
and look for a conch shell

315
00:13:58,372 --> 00:14:00,473
and just have a nice Saturday at the beach.

316
00:14:00,473 --> 00:14:02,215
So everything has to be done that weekend

317
00:14:02,215 --> 00:14:04,256
and there's not enough time to do it all.

318
00:14:04,256 --> 00:14:06,378
And the game is told from Dan's perspective.

319
00:14:06,918 --> 00:14:12,479
So it's presented as a series of choices like these where you can't do everything he wants to do, and you have to pick what's more important.

320
00:14:12,479 --> 00:14:17,921
So after you uncover all the clues, you basically have to decide whether Dan should help with the promo forms,

321
00:14:17,921 --> 00:14:21,082
and so Linda can focus on her last painting and kind of support her in her career.

322
00:14:21,082 --> 00:14:26,063
So you see there she's thinking, you know, he could take care of those promo forms for me,

323
00:14:26,063 --> 00:14:27,723
and that would obviously help the marriage.

324
00:14:27,723 --> 00:14:29,564
Or you could look at, uh...

325
00:14:30,893 --> 00:14:32,894
him just basically going into crunch mode over the weekend

326
00:14:32,894 --> 00:14:35,014
and chaining himself to his typewriter to work on his book,

327
00:14:35,014 --> 00:14:36,995
which of course helps his career and helps his novel.

328
00:14:36,995 --> 00:14:40,595
Or he could blow off both of those things

329
00:14:40,595 --> 00:14:42,196
and take Tommy on the beach trip,

330
00:14:42,196 --> 00:14:43,676
which is good for his role as a parent.

331
00:14:43,676 --> 00:14:46,737
So in this case, let's say the player chooses

332
00:14:46,737 --> 00:14:48,597
to prioritize Dan and Linda's marriage

333
00:14:48,597 --> 00:14:50,117
and work on the promo forms.

334
00:14:50,117 --> 00:14:52,478
These decisions are fed back to the player

335
00:14:52,478 --> 00:14:53,958
through a series of short scenes

336
00:14:53,958 --> 00:14:56,218
that kind of tell you the impact of what happened.

337
00:14:56,859 --> 00:14:58,659
So here we can see that Dan and Linda

338
00:14:58,659 --> 00:14:59,880
are working on the forms together

339
00:14:59,880 --> 00:15:01,541
and it kind of explains, I don't know

340
00:15:01,541 --> 00:15:03,802
how easy that is to read, but it basically goes on to say

341
00:15:03,802 --> 00:15:06,583
the art show was a big hit, the ad in the paper

342
00:15:06,583 --> 00:15:08,584
did a lot to help that happen and it was good

343
00:15:08,584 --> 00:15:11,546
that he helped her and it was really a big boost for her

344
00:15:11,546 --> 00:15:13,487
and it was awesome that he was a supportive husband

345
00:15:13,487 --> 00:15:14,967
and that's really cool.

346
00:15:14,967 --> 00:15:17,108
However, Tommy didn't get his beach trip,

347
00:15:17,108 --> 00:15:20,350
so he spent Saturday looking out the window being super sad

348
00:15:20,350 --> 00:15:22,471
and that's kind of a bummer.

349
00:15:24,093 --> 00:15:32,108
And then Dan also misses his deadline because he spent the time supporting his wife and he gets chewed out by his agent and his book kind of goes a little bit more in the gutter.

350
00:15:33,256 --> 00:15:36,217
So again, the narrative's constructed from the history

351
00:15:36,217 --> 00:15:39,158
of the player's choices on these specific topics.

352
00:15:39,158 --> 00:15:41,459
And so the starting point of the next chapter, in this

353
00:15:41,459 --> 00:15:43,480
case, would be a better marriage because he helped her

354
00:15:43,480 --> 00:15:46,601
with the promo forms, an unhappier child because he

355
00:15:46,601 --> 00:15:49,242
broke that promise to his kid, and a worse book because he

356
00:15:49,242 --> 00:15:50,422
missed his deadline.

357
00:15:50,422 --> 00:15:52,703
And these relationships are the spine of the story.

358
00:15:52,703 --> 00:15:55,584
So I decided that I would build a really simple

359
00:15:55,584 --> 00:15:56,545
simulation of them.

360
00:15:58,200 --> 00:16:00,561
So each of those relationships is scored from 0 to 9,

361
00:16:00,561 --> 00:16:03,102
with 0 being the worst and 9 being the best.

362
00:16:03,102 --> 00:16:05,443
And at the beginning of the game, they're all rated at 5.

363
00:16:05,443 --> 00:16:07,443
So everything comes in even.

364
00:16:07,443 --> 00:16:08,724
And in the example we just looked at,

365
00:16:08,724 --> 00:16:11,565
where Dan supported Linda at the expense of his work

366
00:16:11,565 --> 00:16:12,845
and his relationship to his son.

367
00:16:14,546 --> 00:16:17,809
The marriage score goes up to seven, while his career score

368
00:16:17,809 --> 00:16:19,891
and his relationship to Tommy each drop to four.

369
00:16:19,891 --> 00:16:22,033
And these numbers are never revealed to the player.

370
00:16:22,033 --> 00:16:24,395
They're actually fed back through a variety of other

371
00:16:24,395 --> 00:16:26,177
means that I'll go into a little bit later.

372
00:16:26,177 --> 00:16:27,418
But it's important to know that this

373
00:16:27,418 --> 00:16:28,299
is all under the hood.

374
00:16:28,299 --> 00:16:31,902
So the relationship scores, like I said, are the

375
00:16:31,902 --> 00:16:33,984
connective tissue that carry forward from chapter to

376
00:16:33,984 --> 00:16:35,025
chapter in the game.

377
00:16:35,819 --> 00:16:37,459
And the next decision that the player makes

378
00:16:37,459 --> 00:16:39,320
will be based on starting with these new values.

379
00:16:39,320 --> 00:16:41,580
So if you plot that change over time,

380
00:16:41,580 --> 00:16:43,561
it basically looks like this.

381
00:16:43,561 --> 00:16:46,141
Each decision makes a relationship

382
00:16:46,141 --> 00:16:47,942
get noticeably better or slightly worse.

383
00:16:47,942 --> 00:16:51,882
And so this little Pac-Man mouth is sort of the atomic unit

384
00:16:51,882 --> 00:16:52,563
of the story.

385
00:16:52,563 --> 00:16:55,363
Every decision functions on these relationships

386
00:16:55,363 --> 00:16:58,404
one way or another, either making it pretty much better

387
00:16:58,404 --> 00:16:59,564
or slightly worse.

388
00:17:00,627 --> 00:17:02,748
So the way this works over the course of the game

389
00:17:02,748 --> 00:17:04,428
is that if you look at a game with nine chapters

390
00:17:04,428 --> 00:17:06,509
and they all start at five,

391
00:17:06,509 --> 00:17:08,930
this is the sort of possibility space

392
00:17:08,930 --> 00:17:10,910
of any given relationship over the game.

393
00:17:10,910 --> 00:17:13,371
These are the possible decisions that could happen.

394
00:17:13,371 --> 00:17:15,692
So by the end of the second chapter,

395
00:17:15,692 --> 00:17:17,452
any relationship in the game can actually

396
00:17:17,452 --> 00:17:18,973
already reach its maximal value

397
00:17:18,973 --> 00:17:21,093
because it's five plus two is seven plus two is nine.

398
00:17:21,093 --> 00:17:23,834
So Dan's book could be the next War and Peace

399
00:17:23,834 --> 00:17:25,515
or he and Linda could be on a perpetual honeymoon

400
00:17:25,515 --> 00:17:27,855
or he could also be the greatest dad in the world.

401
00:17:29,022 --> 00:17:30,283
So if we keep going a little further,

402
00:17:30,283 --> 00:17:32,004
you see that from each one of these points,

403
00:17:32,004 --> 00:17:34,866
additional decisions can be made and continue to build out.

404
00:17:34,866 --> 00:17:37,028
And by the fifth chapter, any relationship

405
00:17:37,028 --> 00:17:39,750
that's been completely neglected can hit rock bottom.

406
00:17:39,750 --> 00:17:42,612
It can actually get to the worst shape possible.

407
00:17:42,612 --> 00:17:43,793
If you have ignored that, you know,

408
00:17:43,793 --> 00:17:45,394
either ignored his book or ignored his wife

409
00:17:45,394 --> 00:17:47,856
or ignored his son the whole time.

410
00:17:47,856 --> 00:17:50,358
So we follow forward, and the decisions pile on decisions

411
00:17:50,358 --> 00:17:52,640
pile on decisions, and this represents

412
00:17:52,640 --> 00:17:55,903
the full possibility space for any single relationship

413
00:17:55,903 --> 00:17:56,463
in the game.

414
00:17:57,261 --> 00:17:59,383
And if you compare that to the branching plot diagram,

415
00:17:59,383 --> 00:18:01,045
it actually looks pretty impressive, right?

416
00:18:01,045 --> 00:18:02,427
There's so much stuff you can do.

417
00:18:02,427 --> 00:18:03,728
But it's actually not.

418
00:18:03,728 --> 00:18:04,609
This is kind of a mess.

419
00:18:04,609 --> 00:18:08,734
It's too granular for most of these data points to mean anything.

420
00:18:08,734 --> 00:18:10,476
And since the numbers are never shown to the player,

421
00:18:10,476 --> 00:18:12,198
a lot of this detail is irrelevant.

422
00:18:12,198 --> 00:18:15,101
So while there might be a big possibility space,

423
00:18:15,101 --> 00:18:16,963
it's very hard to tease a lot of meaning out of this.

424
00:18:16,963 --> 00:18:18,465
And in fact, it's just a different form.

425
00:18:18,845 --> 00:18:20,026
of the thing I was trying to avoid,

426
00:18:20,026 --> 00:18:22,468
which is system soup.

427
00:18:22,468 --> 00:18:24,769
So when I realized that, I knew the next challenge

428
00:18:24,769 --> 00:18:27,111
was to basically take these numbers

429
00:18:27,111 --> 00:18:29,513
that were under the hood and very granular

430
00:18:29,513 --> 00:18:31,114
and not fed back very well

431
00:18:31,114 --> 00:18:33,956
and overlay a lot of sort of human-readable context

432
00:18:33,956 --> 00:18:35,958
to let players know where they were standing

433
00:18:35,958 --> 00:18:37,899
and where these relationships were.

434
00:18:37,899 --> 00:18:39,721
So here are some of the methods

435
00:18:39,721 --> 00:18:41,962
that I used to feed this stuff back.

436
00:18:41,962 --> 00:18:42,423
First off...

437
00:18:46,887 --> 00:18:50,088
The player can basically read the character's thoughts and just see what the relationship

438
00:18:50,088 --> 00:18:50,829
statuses are.

439
00:18:50,829 --> 00:18:54,490
So here's one where Tommy is bummed out about his dad.

440
00:18:54,490 --> 00:18:57,631
They don't have a very good relationship and so he's saying, oh, mommy said daddy's just

441
00:18:57,631 --> 00:18:58,232
too busy.

442
00:18:58,232 --> 00:19:01,073
So he, you know, things aren't going well and you can kind of read, oh, wow, that's

443
00:19:01,073 --> 00:19:02,173
kind of a, that kind of hurts him.

444
00:19:02,173 --> 00:19:03,994
Maybe I should give Tommy a little love in this chapter.

445
00:19:04,674 --> 00:19:07,657
You can also explore the characters' memories

446
00:19:07,657 --> 00:19:10,119
and find diaries where they react to previous decisions.

447
00:19:10,119 --> 00:19:14,042
So here's a diary where Linda's really excited about how things went with her art show,

448
00:19:14,042 --> 00:19:18,506
and you kind of get that payoff of how elated she is that things went well for her.

449
00:19:18,506 --> 00:19:22,029
Tommy also does drawings to represent his relationship with his father.

450
00:19:22,029 --> 00:19:23,790
So this is when things are going really good.

451
00:19:23,790 --> 00:19:26,292
He draws happy pictures. Dad's got his arm around him.

452
00:19:27,213 --> 00:19:28,954
Here's where things are kind of just OK.

453
00:19:28,954 --> 00:19:31,817
They're just kind of standing there like, hey, we exist.

454
00:19:31,817 --> 00:19:34,699
And then, uh, this is when things are going really badly.

455
00:19:34,699 --> 00:19:36,140
His dad is like this screaming monster,

456
00:19:36,140 --> 00:19:38,242
and he looks sad. He's giving this what-do-I-do thing.

457
00:19:38,242 --> 00:19:40,764
So it basically shows you the different range

458
00:19:40,764 --> 00:19:42,946
of drawings that Tommy can make.

459
00:19:42,946 --> 00:19:43,466
Um, I also...

460
00:19:44,066 --> 00:19:46,708
did a thing where there are objects left around

461
00:19:46,708 --> 00:19:48,330
from previous chapters in the house.

462
00:19:48,330 --> 00:19:49,711
So this newspaper clipping on the wall

463
00:19:49,711 --> 00:19:52,293
only comes up if you do the art show with Linda.

464
00:19:52,293 --> 00:19:54,035
And if you go read it, it's basically a notice

465
00:19:54,035 --> 00:19:56,417
that says, you know, local artists or visiting artists,

466
00:19:56,417 --> 00:19:58,358
Linda Kaplan put on a great show, blah, blah, blah.

467
00:19:58,358 --> 00:19:59,860
So it kind of gives you a little bit of payoff

468
00:19:59,860 --> 00:20:01,201
to remind you of your past decisions.

469
00:20:01,201 --> 00:20:02,322
And over the course of the game,

470
00:20:02,322 --> 00:20:04,063
these objects build up across the house

471
00:20:04,063 --> 00:20:07,687
and sort of create a unique landscape of the decisions

472
00:20:07,687 --> 00:20:09,808
you've made represented by these physical objects.

473
00:20:09,808 --> 00:20:11,210
Another example would be.

474
00:20:11,370 --> 00:20:14,723
If you had actually taken Tommy to the beach, that conch shell would now be on his bedside

475
00:20:14,723 --> 00:20:15,667
table for the rest of the game.

476
00:20:17,498 --> 00:20:21,683
Another one is that when characters pass each other in the house, they'll greet each other.

477
00:20:21,683 --> 00:20:25,747
So if things are going really well with Dan and Linda, they'll have a really happy greeting.

478
00:20:25,747 --> 00:20:29,450
They'll maybe talk about taking a break together or going into town to get something to eat.

479
00:20:29,450 --> 00:20:31,753
If things are just going okay, it's a lot more perfunctory.

480
00:20:31,753 --> 00:20:32,714
It's just like, hey, oh, hey.

481
00:20:32,714 --> 00:20:37,558
And if things are going bad, they barely acknowledge each other, and it sounds really icy and pretty tough.

482
00:20:37,558 --> 00:20:41,442
So just ambiently around the house, you can kind of hear some representations of those relationships.

483
00:20:42,366 --> 00:20:45,668
And if things get really bad, characters will actually start locking themselves in their rooms.

484
00:20:45,668 --> 00:20:50,750
So this is Tommy in his room alone playing with his toys, sad because his dad's neglecting him.

485
00:20:50,750 --> 00:20:53,152
And Linda can do the same in her studio.

486
00:20:53,152 --> 00:20:56,373
And there's also some scenarios where Dan can do that in his office.

487
00:20:57,314 --> 00:21:01,556
And then this is my favorite one, which I don't think anyone's ever noticed in the world, but I like it.

488
00:21:01,556 --> 00:21:07,479
Dan's trash can. If things are going really good on his book, there's almost no crumbled up paper in his trash can.

489
00:21:07,479 --> 00:21:12,622
But as things start to go worse, it fills back in, and each chapter it kind of represents the status of his book by

490
00:21:12,622 --> 00:21:15,203
how many bad pages are curled up and thrown on the floor.

491
00:21:15,203 --> 00:21:18,045
And, I don't know. Now at least some people know that that exists.

492
00:21:19,454 --> 00:21:21,818
So these things are all good at giving the player status updates.

493
00:21:21,818 --> 00:21:22,299
That's good.

494
00:21:22,299 --> 00:21:23,080
It's information.

495
00:21:23,080 --> 00:21:26,025
The player knows how these relationships are standing, but we still don't have a story.

496
00:21:26,025 --> 00:21:30,472
We still have nine flat chapters without any highs or lows, and you just sort of manipulate

497
00:21:30,472 --> 00:21:33,857
these relationships, but it's just the same sort of flow over and over again.

498
00:21:34,645 --> 00:21:37,026
And one of the key benefits of an authored story

499
00:21:37,026 --> 00:21:39,827
is that the writer can make sure the story has a beginning

500
00:21:39,827 --> 00:21:40,627
and middle and an end.

501
00:21:40,627 --> 00:21:43,388
They can make sure to modulate the intensity of the events

502
00:21:43,388 --> 00:21:45,008
and create some dramatic ebb and flow

503
00:21:45,008 --> 00:21:47,049
so that the story has some structure

504
00:21:47,049 --> 00:21:48,650
and players are kept more interested

505
00:21:48,650 --> 00:21:50,330
and you kind of have these big events

506
00:21:50,330 --> 00:21:51,791
and then you release with some pressure

507
00:21:51,791 --> 00:21:53,151
and release the pressure and then build up

508
00:21:53,151 --> 00:21:55,912
to another big event and basically modulate the flow

509
00:21:55,912 --> 00:21:58,033
so players don't get fatigued but they also feel structure.

510
00:21:58,714 --> 00:22:03,099
And there are a lot of ways to do this, but one of the most basic is the traditional 3x structure,

511
00:22:03,099 --> 00:22:08,385
which is a very simple way of creating rising and falling action over time,

512
00:22:08,385 --> 00:22:10,867
and building to a climax and resolution.

513
00:22:10,867 --> 00:22:13,711
Now, this is super, super basic. It's not innovative at all.

514
00:22:13,711 --> 00:22:17,395
And a lot of writers actually advocate moving away from it and going to more advanced forms.

515
00:22:17,995 --> 00:22:20,936
But in the case of my game, given the difficulty

516
00:22:20,936 --> 00:22:22,737
of trying to create a narrative out of these really

517
00:22:22,737 --> 00:22:25,297
unpredictable systems, where I don't know what order

518
00:22:25,297 --> 00:22:26,618
the events are going to happen in,

519
00:22:26,618 --> 00:22:29,979
I don't know what the player's going to choose each time,

520
00:22:29,979 --> 00:22:31,339
I actually felt that having something

521
00:22:31,339 --> 00:22:33,700
that's very identifiable and very recognizable in a form

522
00:22:33,700 --> 00:22:35,580
that people get would actually help.

523
00:22:35,580 --> 00:22:37,481
So this did not feel like the place for me

524
00:22:37,481 --> 00:22:38,421
to try to do something weird.

525
00:22:38,421 --> 00:22:40,562
I actually thought the game benefited

526
00:22:40,562 --> 00:22:43,123
from having a really simple, defined structure based

527
00:22:43,123 --> 00:22:43,803
on the three acts.

528
00:22:45,104 --> 00:22:49,442
So the more familiarity and form I could add to the story, I felt that was better.

529
00:22:50,960 --> 00:22:53,881
So if we look at our map of the possibility space again

530
00:22:53,881 --> 00:22:56,442
and slice it to have three acts and a climax,

531
00:22:56,442 --> 00:22:59,004
then we can start to see specific points in the narrative

532
00:22:59,004 --> 00:23:00,905
and the timeline that we start to build up to.

533
00:23:00,905 --> 00:23:03,166
And if we slice it into three acts,

534
00:23:03,166 --> 00:23:05,947
we can also zero in on where those relationship scores

535
00:23:05,947 --> 00:23:08,008
can be at any of these points in the story.

536
00:23:08,008 --> 00:23:11,810
So we start to identify, I wanna punch things up here

537
00:23:11,810 --> 00:23:14,371
and this is sort of where things can be at this time.

538
00:23:14,371 --> 00:23:16,573
And we can start to isolate places

539
00:23:16,573 --> 00:23:19,174
to put bigger and more memorable moments in the story

540
00:23:19,174 --> 00:23:20,675
to try to give it those peaks and valleys.

541
00:23:22,941 --> 00:23:25,402
And I used the three-act structure as a guide

542
00:23:25,402 --> 00:23:27,102
to introduce more drama at known intervals.

543
00:23:27,102 --> 00:23:29,963
And the way I did that was I made chapters three

544
00:23:29,963 --> 00:23:32,304
and six and eight higher-stakes dilemmas.

545
00:23:32,304 --> 00:23:35,865
They were generally more, uh, I don't know,

546
00:23:35,865 --> 00:23:37,446
emotionally-involving chapters,

547
00:23:37,446 --> 00:23:39,086
and each one of them focused on a different character.

548
00:23:39,086 --> 00:23:41,207
And then chapter nine is the finale,

549
00:23:41,207 --> 00:23:43,648
so it sort of has the highest stakes of all.

550
00:23:43,648 --> 00:23:45,568
Um, and since the game takes place over one summer,

551
00:23:45,568 --> 00:23:47,189
I felt like there was a natural rhythm to it

552
00:23:47,189 --> 00:23:49,269
where I could just say, well, June is act one,

553
00:23:49,269 --> 00:23:51,390
July is act two, and August is act three,

554
00:23:51,390 --> 00:23:52,490
culminating with them.

555
00:23:52,591 --> 00:23:55,067
leaving the house and going forward into the future.

556
00:23:58,945 --> 00:24:02,327
So I started to do this, but I realized, you know, maybe, so, so,

557
00:24:02,327 --> 00:24:06,730
the bottle is an example of one of these high stakes chapters.

558
00:24:06,730 --> 00:24:10,692
It's one where Dan's drinking problem is getting a little bit out of control.

559
00:24:10,692 --> 00:24:14,715
His wife's worried about him. His son's upset because he's not paying enough attention to him.

560
00:24:14,715 --> 00:24:17,997
And I decided to set all these high stakes chapters at night.

561
00:24:17,997 --> 00:24:20,618
The game has different times of day, so I figured why not make it at night?

562
00:24:20,618 --> 00:24:23,000
Make it feel more ominous. Make it feel more heavy.

563
00:24:23,000 --> 00:24:23,340
And so...

564
00:24:24,240 --> 00:24:26,603
I made sure to put these at chapters 3, 6, and 9.

565
00:24:26,603 --> 00:24:28,445
They're still randomly selected.

566
00:24:28,445 --> 00:24:30,648
There's a bucket of these, and I put a random one at each time,

567
00:24:30,648 --> 00:24:32,010
so it's not like I really structure it that much.

568
00:24:32,010 --> 00:24:33,692
But I just make sure that something big

569
00:24:33,692 --> 00:24:36,054
happens at these key points in the story.

570
00:24:36,054 --> 00:24:37,616
And I also make sure that after that,

571
00:24:37,616 --> 00:24:39,919
it pulls from the bucket of lower stakes chapters,

572
00:24:39,919 --> 00:24:41,781
so that you get some peaks and then a little bit

573
00:24:41,781 --> 00:24:42,842
of release of that tension.

574
00:24:43,789 --> 00:24:46,871
And in addition, this was another thing that I added

575
00:24:46,871 --> 00:24:48,553
after a lot of playtest feedback,

576
00:24:48,553 --> 00:24:50,474
was after each one of these high-stakes chapters,

577
00:24:50,474 --> 00:24:52,956
you get an additional set of these narrative wrap-up scenes

578
00:24:52,956 --> 00:24:54,677
that give you sort of a roll-up

579
00:24:54,677 --> 00:24:57,459
on the overall relationship status of all these axes

580
00:24:57,459 --> 00:24:59,781
that aren't related to any specific chapter.

581
00:25:00,681 --> 00:25:02,903
So they take place completely off screen,

582
00:25:02,903 --> 00:25:07,026
and they serve as a summary of all the choices the players made up to this point.

583
00:25:07,026 --> 00:25:10,889
So it's not just, here's how people reacted to the choice you just made for this chapter,

584
00:25:10,889 --> 00:25:14,011
but here's where your relationships stand based on all of your choices so far.

585
00:25:15,632 --> 00:25:17,853
So, it wasn't feasible scope-wise, obviously,

586
00:25:17,853 --> 00:25:20,154
to create scenes for every possible relationship score.

587
00:25:20,154 --> 00:25:21,795
It might have worked okay at the first

588
00:25:21,795 --> 00:25:22,876
because there's not that many options,

589
00:25:22,876 --> 00:25:25,557
but by the second act and certainly by the third act,

590
00:25:25,557 --> 00:25:27,578
there would literally be 10 options for both

591
00:25:27,578 --> 00:25:29,839
because every relationship could be everywhere,

592
00:25:29,839 --> 00:25:31,460
and that's completely...

593
00:25:31,980 --> 00:25:33,201
you know, unsustainable from a scope,

594
00:25:33,201 --> 00:25:36,084
especially from a one dude making a game in his apartment.

595
00:25:36,084 --> 00:25:38,226
So that wasn't necessarily a problem, though,

596
00:25:38,226 --> 00:25:40,288
because these would be so granular anyways

597
00:25:40,288 --> 00:25:41,970
that I'm not sure the player would know the difference

598
00:25:41,970 --> 00:25:43,732
between what's a, what's a six relationship

599
00:25:43,732 --> 00:25:45,694
and what's a seven relationship.

600
00:25:45,694 --> 00:25:48,416
So what I did was, I broke this up into bands.

601
00:25:48,816 --> 00:25:53,859
that basically denoted different relationship values,

602
00:25:53,859 --> 00:25:57,021
and then broke those down into, you know,

603
00:25:57,021 --> 00:25:57,701
8 and 9 are good, 6 and 7,

604
00:25:57,701 --> 00:26:00,583
or 8 and 9 is great, 6 or 7 is good,

605
00:26:00,583 --> 00:26:03,104
3, 4, and 5 are bad, and 0, 1, and 2 are awful.

606
00:26:04,587 --> 00:26:08,808
I broke it down into categories to kind of make them work more manageable, but also because

607
00:26:08,808 --> 00:26:12,469
that way they would actually make sense to characters. You can tell the difference between

608
00:26:12,469 --> 00:26:16,250
good and bad a lot more than you can tell the difference between four and five or something

609
00:26:16,250 --> 00:26:21,831
like that. So it basically preserved the granular relationship scoring under the hood while

610
00:26:21,831 --> 00:26:25,732
compressing the dynamic range of the player feedback into something that was more meaningful

611
00:26:25,732 --> 00:26:28,673
to players. So here's an example of some of those scenes.

612
00:26:29,238 --> 00:26:30,779
You start off with a little intro that says,

613
00:26:30,779 --> 00:26:34,362
hey, the first month is done, and a lot of stuff had happened.

614
00:26:34,362 --> 00:26:36,424
And then you get three scenes that

615
00:26:36,424 --> 00:26:38,245
tell you the status of these relationships

616
00:26:38,245 --> 00:26:40,647
based on all of the decisions up to this point.

617
00:26:40,647 --> 00:26:44,150
So for example, at the end of the first act,

618
00:26:44,150 --> 00:26:46,492
Dan sends his work in progress to his agent.

619
00:26:46,492 --> 00:26:48,054
And his agent comes back and says, oh, wow.

620
00:26:48,054 --> 00:26:48,794
This is really great.

621
00:26:48,794 --> 00:26:49,535
This is awesome.

622
00:26:49,535 --> 00:26:51,577
So you know that Dan's book is going well

623
00:26:51,577 --> 00:26:54,379
at the end of the first act of the game.

624
00:26:54,379 --> 00:26:56,681
Dan and Linda go into town for a date.

625
00:26:56,701 --> 00:26:57,862
the date goes really well.

626
00:26:57,862 --> 00:27:00,064
So you say, oh man, I guess they really are hitting it off.

627
00:27:00,064 --> 00:27:02,686
I'm so glad I'm saving this relationship as the player

628
00:27:02,686 --> 00:27:04,827
based on the choices I made.

