00:27:04,827 --> 00:27:07,589
But here's a story, a sad story, where

630
00:27:07,589 --> 00:27:09,391
Dan took Tommy out in the woods to look for arrowheads.

631
00:27:09,391 --> 00:27:11,112
And basically, as soon as they got there, he said, OK, come

632
00:27:11,112 --> 00:27:11,853
on, we're going home.

633
00:27:11,853 --> 00:27:12,733
And Tommy was crying.

634
00:27:12,733 --> 00:27:13,854
Dan didn't care.

635
00:27:13,854 --> 00:27:16,576
And so it basically says that, yeah, he's up to this point

636
00:27:16,576 --> 00:27:17,898
being a very neglectful father.

637
00:27:17,898 --> 00:27:20,680
And there are four different versions of

638
00:27:20,680 --> 00:27:22,001
each of these scenes.

639
00:27:22,001 --> 00:27:24,363
So depending on where those relationships are in those

640
00:27:24,363 --> 00:27:24,603
zones.

641
00:27:24,815 --> 00:27:26,396
then you get one of those four scenes.

642
00:27:26,396 --> 00:27:28,958
That's a lot more manageable than 10 scenes each time.

643
00:27:28,958 --> 00:27:30,900
And arguably, it's more readable to the player.

644
00:27:30,900 --> 00:27:33,842
And they really explicitly tell you how things are going.

645
00:27:33,842 --> 00:27:35,224
So you get these at the end of, you

646
00:27:35,224 --> 00:27:36,865
have these big, high stakes chapters.

647
00:27:36,865 --> 00:27:38,366
And then you get a roll up that says,

648
00:27:38,366 --> 00:27:39,187
here you are in the story.

649
00:27:39,187 --> 00:27:40,148
Here's where it is.

650
00:27:40,148 --> 00:27:41,689
And you're like, wow, end of a month.

651
00:27:41,689 --> 00:27:43,571
And it kind of gives you a good place to stop.

652
00:27:43,571 --> 00:27:46,213
Like a lot of people will play an act,

653
00:27:46,213 --> 00:27:48,035
and then put the game down, and play the next act,

654
00:27:48,035 --> 00:27:48,815
put the game down.

655
00:27:49,400 --> 00:27:51,342
It really did a good job of starting to split the game up

656
00:27:51,342 --> 00:27:53,224
into a more definable structure,

657
00:27:53,224 --> 00:27:58,448
so that there was some rising and falling action.

658
00:27:58,448 --> 00:27:58,568
So...

659
00:27:58,568 --> 00:28:01,030
Once I got to this point,

660
00:28:01,030 --> 00:28:03,352
the system was actually in pretty good shape.

661
00:28:03,352 --> 00:28:05,754
Players understood how their decisions and actions

662
00:28:05,754 --> 00:28:07,155
were creating the story.

663
00:28:07,155 --> 00:28:10,318
I was starting to get to a discernible narrative flow,

664
00:28:10,318 --> 00:28:11,999
and there was a beginning, a middle, and an end,

665
00:28:11,999 --> 00:28:14,301
and the players had an emotional connection to the experience.

666
00:28:15,449 --> 00:28:17,931
And I was happy for a while, but unfortunately,

667
00:28:17,931 --> 00:28:19,592
while the core system was pretty solid,

668
00:28:19,592 --> 00:28:21,654
it started to reveal some limitations.

669
00:28:21,654 --> 00:28:23,516
And these started to come mostly from

670
00:28:23,516 --> 00:28:25,677
players' sort of natural expectations

671
00:28:25,677 --> 00:28:27,399
regarding how human beings would actually react

672
00:28:27,399 --> 00:28:28,360
in some of these scenarios.

673
00:28:28,360 --> 00:28:31,242
So let's take a look at a scenario where the player

