00:30:16,122 --> 00:30:19,303
and get to the same decision point here and

721
00:30:19,303 --> 00:30:21,864
apply these same scoring zones that I was using

722
00:30:21,864 --> 00:30:23,484
for the, the act break wrap ups.

723
00:30:23,484 --> 00:30:26,825
So we can use these inflection points as triggers

724
00:30:26,825 --> 00:30:28,285
to know when the characters should speak up for

725
00:30:28,285 --> 00:30:31,406
each other. So, for example, Linda sees that Tommy

726
00:30:31,406 --> 00:30:33,486
has just crossed into the awful zone, like things

727
00:30:33,486 --> 00:30:35,207
are going really bad, and she decides to do

728
00:30:35,207 --> 00:30:36,707
something about it.

729
00:30:36,707 --> 00:30:39,148
So in this scenario, instead of her wanting her

730
00:30:39,148 --> 00:30:41,048
desired outcome in a vacuum, which is what we

731
00:30:41,048 --> 00:30:42,648
saw before, she says, wow, I wish Dan could

732
00:30:42,648 --> 00:30:44,609
take care of those promo forms so I could

733
00:30:44,609 --> 00:30:45,389
work on my painting.

734
00:30:46,781 --> 00:30:48,161
Instead, she says,

735
00:30:48,161 --> 00:30:49,542
he shouldn't worry about those promo forms.

736
00:30:49,542 --> 00:30:51,262
He really should take Tommy to get that shell.

737
00:30:51,262 --> 00:30:52,943
She speaks up for Tommy and tells the player

738
00:30:52,943 --> 00:30:54,823
very explicitly, hey, this is what I want,

739
00:30:54,823 --> 00:30:55,703
but I don't want you to do it.

740
00:30:55,703 --> 00:30:56,924
I want you to take care of your son.

741
00:30:56,924 --> 00:30:59,624
So this is like a feedback mechanism in the game,

742
00:30:59,624 --> 00:31:02,345
and it was originally just intended

743
00:31:02,345 --> 00:31:04,806
to make the characters more believable.

744
00:31:04,806 --> 00:31:06,706
But I quickly realized that I had to

745
00:31:06,706 --> 00:31:08,547
incorporate those intentions back

746
00:31:08,547 --> 00:31:09,787
into the simulation itself.

747
00:31:09,787 --> 00:31:11,828
It wasn't good enough for them to just speak up.

748
00:31:12,066 --> 00:31:15,168
So in a normal case, obviously if none of the relationships

749
00:31:15,168 --> 00:31:16,809
are in the awful zone and nothing's been triggered,

750
00:31:16,809 --> 00:31:18,891
then each character just wants what they want in a vacuum,

751
00:31:18,891 --> 00:31:21,192
like we saw with Linda before.

752
00:31:21,192 --> 00:31:23,414
But here, Linda has changed her mind and says

753
00:31:23,414 --> 00:31:25,115
she wants Dan to pay attention to their son,

754
00:31:25,115 --> 00:31:28,097
not do what she would actually normally want.

755
00:31:28,097 --> 00:31:30,179
So if the player listens to Linda's request

756
00:31:30,179 --> 00:31:31,820
and goes and plays with Tommy,

757
00:31:31,820 --> 00:31:33,461
Tommy gets the normal two-point boost

758
00:31:33,461 --> 00:31:36,043
that pulls his relationship back out of the awful band.

759
00:31:36,043 --> 00:31:37,944
It's still bad, but it's better than nothing.

760
00:31:39,670 --> 00:31:43,153
But the key thing is that Linda doesn't take the normal one point hit.

761
00:31:43,153 --> 00:31:46,116
Which stands to reason. She was very clear about what she wanted.

762
00:31:46,116 --> 00:31:49,278
And she said, you know, my desire is for you to put Tommy in front of my own needs.

763
00:31:49,278 --> 00:31:53,281
And it would be a really bad simulation if the player got such a clear message from Linda,

764
00:31:53,281 --> 00:31:57,925
did what Linda wanted, and then she still turned around and got mad at him for not doing what she wanted.

765
00:31:57,925 --> 00:32:01,989
So, in essence, the simulation allows Linda to forgive Dan in conditional cases where

766
00:32:01,989 --> 00:32:06,312
she had actually said, hey, you know what, what I want isn't the most important thing right now.

767
00:32:07,750 --> 00:32:09,773
And on the flip side, if we look at the same situation,

768
00:32:09,773 --> 00:32:12,117
and Linda says, you should take care of your son,

769
00:32:12,117 --> 00:32:13,879
forget my promo forms, and Dan says, shut up,

770
00:32:13,879 --> 00:32:15,501
I'm doing the promo forms anyways.

771
00:32:16,077 --> 00:32:18,518
Then Tommy's relationship score still takes that one point hit.

772
00:32:18,518 --> 00:32:20,479
It still gets worse because he still got ignored.

773
00:32:20,479 --> 00:32:22,540
Belinda also takes the hit.

774
00:32:22,540 --> 00:32:23,900
She gets angry about it.

775
00:32:23,900 --> 00:32:25,081
She says, I told you, you jerk.

776
00:32:25,081 --> 00:32:26,321
You know, pay attention to your son,

777
00:32:26,321 --> 00:32:27,942
and you just went and did this anyways.

778
00:32:27,942 --> 00:32:28,662
How deaf are you?

779
00:32:28,662 --> 00:32:31,823
And there are actually conditional outcomes

780
00:32:31,823 --> 00:32:33,264
for all the chapters that address this.

781
00:32:33,264 --> 00:32:35,505
If you go either way in this scenario,

782
00:32:35,505 --> 00:32:36,545
then in the next chapter, it's fed back.

783
00:32:36,545 --> 00:32:38,026
And she says, you know, I really would

784
00:32:38,026 --> 00:32:39,326
have liked to have help with that,

785
00:32:39,326 --> 00:32:40,707
but I'm so glad that Tommy and Dan had a good time

786
00:32:40,707 --> 00:32:42,187
at the beach and blah, blah, blah.

787
00:32:42,648 --> 00:32:43,969
And this works both ways.

788
00:32:43,969 --> 00:32:47,072
If Linda's relationship gets really low and Tommy's is high,

789
00:32:47,072 --> 00:32:49,294
then he'll say, I don't want to go to the beach.

790
00:32:49,294 --> 00:32:50,055
Go make up with mommy.

791
00:32:50,055 --> 00:32:51,517
So they kind of regulate for each other.

792
00:32:51,517 --> 00:32:54,339
Because since the player doesn't have direct control over them

793
00:32:54,339 --> 00:32:55,861
in the way they do over Dan, they

794
00:32:55,861 --> 00:32:58,363
have to have some level of autonomy.

795
00:32:59,164 --> 00:33:01,825
I had to modify the simulation sum to account for edge cases,

796
00:33:01,825 --> 00:33:06,026
and also to make sure that the simulation stayed believable.

797
00:33:06,026 --> 00:33:07,606
And I was happy with how the players,

798
00:33:07,606 --> 00:33:09,747
or how the characters that the player can't control

799
00:33:09,747 --> 00:33:12,267
started to behave in these scenarios.

800
00:33:12,267 --> 00:33:15,048
And in general, the system seemed really tight.

801
00:33:15,048 --> 00:33:17,709
But there was something that still bothered me,

802
00:33:17,709 --> 00:33:20,950
and it started causing a lot of complaints for playtesters as well.

803
00:33:20,950 --> 00:33:21,430
And that's the fact that,

804
00:33:21,430 --> 00:33:25,611
this is probably the biggest one that really took a lot of thought,

805
00:33:25,611 --> 00:33:28,072
because the relationship system is zero-sum.

806
00:33:29,352 --> 00:33:32,876
The player starts with 15 points in the system.

807
00:33:32,876 --> 00:33:35,559
And every choice just reassigns the same number of points.

808
00:33:35,559 --> 00:33:37,181
So 5 plus 5 plus 5 equals 15.

809
00:33:37,181 --> 00:33:38,743
So does 7 plus 4 plus 4.

810
00:33:38,743 --> 00:33:42,728
So over the course of a game, you

811
00:33:42,728 --> 00:33:44,550
start everybody's at level 5, which

812
00:33:44,550 --> 00:33:45,951
is at the top of the bad zone.

813
00:33:45,951 --> 00:33:47,173
That's why they're here.

814
00:33:47,173 --> 00:33:48,635
Things aren't going too well for any of them.

815
00:33:49,750 --> 00:33:52,534
And then, in a zero-sum system, the player is just

816
00:33:52,534 --> 00:33:55,597
spending this entire game rearranging the deck chairs on the Titanic.

817
00:33:55,597 --> 00:33:59,462
So to improve one relationship, you have to make the other two worse.

818
00:33:59,462 --> 00:34:02,165
And so, as you go through the game, you're just moving around

819
00:34:02,165 --> 00:34:04,908
the same fifteen relationship points, making one score better

820
00:34:04,908 --> 00:34:07,351
and the other score is worse. And so in this example,

821
00:34:08,092 --> 00:34:09,193
For Dan to write a great book,

822
00:34:09,193 --> 00:34:10,675
he has to be an awful father,

823
00:34:10,675 --> 00:34:12,637
and he ends up in the exact same spot with Linda.

824
00:34:12,637 --> 00:34:14,279
They're both at a five, it's kind of bad,

825
00:34:14,279 --> 00:34:15,420
and nothing has happened.

826
00:34:15,420 --> 00:34:18,483
So it's this really, really nihilistic viewpoint

827
00:34:18,483 --> 00:34:20,185
from the systems design, right?

828
00:34:20,185 --> 00:34:24,249
You're just saying like, wow, you just have this.

829
00:34:25,092 --> 00:34:30,337
set reserve of emotional energy that you can't spread around you can't make any extra effort in life is just sort of this.

830
00:34:30,337 --> 00:34:33,320
I don't know ugly thing and so.

831
00:34:33,320 --> 00:34:40,828
Players are responding to this and I was like oh well because in my head I was just like oh this is such so simple and beautiful it's plus 2 minus 1 every time it just.

832
00:34:41,048 --> 00:34:47,213
But then I asked myself, you know, when I'm mapping this to relational contexts, does

833
00:34:47,213 --> 00:34:50,756
that represent real life? Is there really no way that you can have a good career and

834
00:34:50,756 --> 00:34:55,861
have a good family? I was like, I know friends that do this. Like, I know it's not impossible.

835
00:34:55,861 --> 00:35:01,145
And I didn't think that that was the right message for the game to send. And I had this

836
00:35:01,145 --> 00:35:02,466
realization where...

837
00:35:03,503 --> 00:35:05,744
I'd done everything I could to advocate authorship

838
00:35:05,744 --> 00:35:07,345
in terms of the narrative content.

839
00:35:07,345 --> 00:35:08,145
I tried my hardest.

840
00:35:08,145 --> 00:35:09,306
I'm sure I didn't succeed everywhere,

841
00:35:09,306 --> 00:35:12,207
but I tried my hardest to make all these situations

842
00:35:12,207 --> 00:35:13,228
very sympathetic.

843
00:35:13,228 --> 00:35:14,688
You, in every chapter, you said,

844
00:35:14,688 --> 00:35:16,549
oh, I can see why, you know, Linda would want this.

845
00:35:16,549 --> 00:35:17,790
I would see why Dan would want this.

846
00:35:17,790 --> 00:35:19,711
And I could see why Tommy wanted this.

847
00:35:19,711 --> 00:35:21,091
And it's up to you, the player, to decide.

848
00:35:21,091 --> 00:35:23,492
I tried to make that as balanced as possible.

849
00:35:23,492 --> 00:35:25,693
But when I hit this problem with the zero-sum system,

850
00:35:25,693 --> 00:35:27,914
I realized that I couldn't advocate authorship

851
00:35:27,914 --> 00:35:28,855
from the game as a whole.

852
00:35:29,315 --> 00:35:32,596
I'd only relocated my authorship from the narrative content

853
00:35:32,596 --> 00:35:34,656
to the actual design of the narrative simulation.

854
00:35:34,656 --> 00:35:38,637
And further, I created a game that was sending a message

855
00:35:38,637 --> 00:35:39,597
that I never intended.

856
00:35:39,597 --> 00:35:41,438
I, I built this relationship simulation,

857
00:35:41,438 --> 00:35:43,698
and I felt like Clark Griswold when he plugs in

858
00:35:43,698 --> 00:35:45,719
the Christmas lights and the house doesn't light up.

859
00:35:45,719 --> 00:35:49,860
The system design had become the implicit message of the game,

860
00:35:49,860 --> 00:35:51,060
and I was basically telling players,

861
00:35:51,060 --> 00:35:52,021
you can't have it all.

862
00:35:52,021 --> 00:35:52,941
Life is zero-sum.

863
00:35:52,941 --> 00:35:53,801
You cannot win.

864
00:35:53,801 --> 00:35:55,141
And it was this really brutal...

865
00:35:56,402 --> 00:35:58,423
Bummer of a game, unintentional.

866
00:35:58,423 --> 00:36:02,765
And so I'm standing there like, why are the lights not coming on?

867
00:36:02,765 --> 00:36:03,906
But yeah, so it was really upsetting.

868
00:36:03,906 --> 00:36:07,327
And the biggest thing is I don't believe that perspective to be true.

869
00:36:07,327 --> 00:36:11,089
I believe you can put in the extra effort and have a better life.

870
00:36:12,030 --> 00:36:14,993
people were taking this message from the game that I fundamentally disagreed with.

871
00:36:14,993 --> 00:36:17,755
And I was like, oh my god, I made this, and I don't agree with it.

872
00:36:17,755 --> 00:36:20,918
And I realized I was editorializing through systems design.

873
00:36:20,918 --> 00:36:24,362
Like, the actual design of the system had become the message of the game.

874
00:36:24,362 --> 00:36:27,285
So I knew I had to make a change, and I started talking to my friends

875
00:36:27,285 --> 00:36:29,547
and thinking about people who actually do seem to have it all.

876
00:36:29,547 --> 00:36:32,129
People who are successful at their jobs, and have a loving wife,

877
00:36:32,129 --> 00:36:33,651
and have a great relationship with their kids.

878
00:36:34,031 --> 00:36:35,873
And I asked myself, how do they do it?

879
00:36:35,873 --> 00:36:38,074
And the answer is actually pretty simple.

880
00:36:38,074 --> 00:36:40,236
They just try harder.

881
00:36:40,236 --> 00:36:42,518
If a parent misses their kid's soccer practice,

882
00:36:42,518 --> 00:36:44,819
then they might take their kid out for ice cream the next day

883
00:36:44,819 --> 00:36:46,761
or take him to a movie to make up for it.

884
00:36:46,761 --> 00:36:48,922
Or if you can't make time to have dinner with your partner,

885
00:36:48,922 --> 00:36:51,344
maybe you buy them a little gift somewhere in the week

886
00:36:51,344 --> 00:36:53,686
or maybe cook them a surprise meal later to make up for it

887
00:36:53,686 --> 00:36:56,388
and say, hey, you know, I knew I couldn't make it when we wanted to,

888
00:36:56,388 --> 00:36:57,809
but you're so important, I want to show it.

889
00:36:57,809 --> 00:36:59,610
And, you know, everybody knows

890
00:36:59,610 --> 00:37:01,072
that you can't please everyone all the time,

891
00:37:01,072 --> 00:37:02,653
but if you do those extra things...

892
00:37:03,063 --> 00:37:30,198
You actually can have a good relationship over time by sort of, you know, a friend of mine said a really, a really great thing, which was the goal isn't to live a balanced week. It's to live a balanced life. So it's just an acknowledgement that you can't please everyone in every situation. If you miss a deadline at work, maybe you stay later to work on it. So you find ways to put in the extra effort to make these make these things go a little better. So that's where the compromise system came into the game and the goal I had was I wanted to.

893
00:37:30,933 --> 00:37:33,767
map the concept of extra effort in life.

894
00:37:34,142 --> 00:37:37,004
to extra effort and skillfulness in the game.

895
00:37:37,004 --> 00:37:38,484
And so for extra effort,

896
00:37:38,484 --> 00:37:40,645
I decided that the player would have to

897
00:37:40,645 --> 00:37:42,126
go down a character's entire clue chain

898
00:37:42,126 --> 00:37:44,827
and find their clue and understand what they wanted to do

899
00:37:44,827 --> 00:37:46,528
in order to earn a compromise with them.

900
00:37:46,528 --> 00:37:49,609
And for skillfulness, they had to also remain unspotted.

901
00:37:49,609 --> 00:37:52,411
So they had to make it through the entire chapter.

902
00:37:52,411 --> 00:37:54,772
It's a stealth game, without being spotted.

903
00:37:54,772 --> 00:37:56,533
So you can't upset the character too much.

904
00:37:56,533 --> 00:37:57,613
They've still got to be in a good place.

905
00:37:57,613 --> 00:37:59,614
And if you do both of those things,

906
00:37:59,614 --> 00:38:01,935
you earn the ability to create a compromise with them.

907
00:38:01,935 --> 00:38:02,115
So...

908
00:38:03,300 --> 00:38:09,063
Remember the scene of Tommy sitting by the window where he's sad because his dad decided to do the promo forms instead and broke the promise to him?

909
00:38:09,063 --> 00:38:13,704
Well, now I implemented a system where if you discover his clue, find out what he wants to do,

910
00:38:13,704 --> 00:38:19,407
and you remain unspotted, then you get the ability to have a compromise with Tommy.

911
00:38:19,857 --> 00:38:23,000
So even if he can't take Tommy down to the beach for the whole day,

912
00:38:23,000 --> 00:38:26,664
he can at least work late and make a little extra time to take him for an hour and a half.

913
00:38:26,664 --> 00:38:30,668
And it's not all that Tommy wanted, but it does show Tommy that he's loved

914
00:38:30,668 --> 00:38:33,931
and that, you know, Dan is trying. He's trying to, you know, do better for everybody.

915
00:38:33,931 --> 00:38:38,136
And just like Linda speaking up for Tommy in the example before,

916
00:38:38,136 --> 00:38:41,459
this needed to be reflected in the simulation itself.

917
00:38:43,831 --> 00:38:50,336
So in the relationship system as it stood, you know, choosing Dan and Linda's marriage would cause a one-point drop on the novel and on Parenthood.

918
00:38:50,336 --> 00:38:55,240
But in the updated simulation, if the player finds a compromise that lets Dan make it up to Tommy in some way,

919
00:38:55,240 --> 00:39:02,246
then the Parenthood score would actually stay the same and not decrease by one, which, if you notice, all of a sudden adds a point to the system.

920
00:39:02,246 --> 00:39:07,230
I just think of them as happiness points because the more you have, the sort of happier you can distribute them through the system.

921
00:39:07,867 --> 00:39:11,209
And so whenever you start adding points to the system

922
00:39:11,209 --> 00:39:12,349
and using compromises effectively,

923
00:39:12,349 --> 00:39:14,390
you can actually please everyone

924
00:39:14,390 --> 00:39:16,551
and get a happy ending to the game.

925
00:39:16,551 --> 00:39:19,673
So remember our atomic unit of every decision in the game

926
00:39:19,673 --> 00:39:21,574
where something either goes up by two or down by one.

927
00:39:21,574 --> 00:39:23,635
Well now we added in a third option

928
00:39:23,635 --> 00:39:25,936
where things could also stay the same.

929
00:39:25,936 --> 00:39:27,577
And if you spread those out over time,

930
00:39:27,577 --> 00:39:30,458
you can actually have a much, much different picture

931
00:39:30,458 --> 00:39:31,519
of the story you're telling.

932
00:39:31,519 --> 00:39:34,520
So here's the possibility space without compromises.

933
00:39:35,404 --> 00:39:37,265
here's the possibility space with compromises.

934
00:39:37,265 --> 00:39:38,965
As soon as you get something to a level,

935
00:39:38,965 --> 00:39:41,046
you can keep it there for the rest of the game

936
00:39:41,046 --> 00:39:43,047
and you can always sort of preserve.

937
00:39:43,047 --> 00:39:45,828
And again, that's not to say that this is better

938
00:39:45,828 --> 00:39:47,548
in and of itself, but it does give the player

939
00:39:47,548 --> 00:39:50,089
more opportunities to impact the narrative.

940
00:39:50,089 --> 00:39:51,430
So in the previous system, again,

941
00:39:51,430 --> 00:39:53,630
the player was just rearranging the same 15 points

942
00:39:53,630 --> 00:39:54,911
throughout the game.

943
00:39:54,911 --> 00:39:56,531
So at the top, you can see the totals.

944
00:39:56,531 --> 00:40:01,633
It's just the same amount of points.

945
00:40:01,633 --> 00:40:03,494
But in the new system, if you use a compromise

946
00:40:03,494 --> 00:40:04,114
in each chapter,

947
00:40:05,222 --> 00:40:07,284
then you see it here for example,

948
00:40:07,284 --> 00:40:10,807
the parenthood rating of 5 stayed the same instead of going down.

949
00:40:10,807 --> 00:40:14,030
And so if you use these carefully throughout the whole game,

950
00:40:14,030 --> 00:40:16,052
then you can slowly increase their happiness.

951
00:40:17,335 --> 00:40:20,197
And by the end of the game, you've got 24 points in the system,

952
00:40:20,197 --> 00:40:22,199
and you can actually have a happy ending for everybody,

953
00:40:22,199 --> 00:40:24,520
because you manage your points, and you're a good person,

954
00:40:24,520 --> 00:40:28,483
and you love them all, and extra effort pays off, and life is awesome.

955
00:40:28,483 --> 00:40:33,086
So the compromise system, I would say, is definitely my favorite piece of message through design in the game,

956
00:40:33,086 --> 00:40:37,269
because it maps a real-world inspiration, which is making the extra effort,

957
00:40:37,269 --> 00:40:43,133
into a game system of making the extra effort, and being careful, and being skillful in your gameplay.

958
00:40:43,554 --> 00:40:45,614
And it also, and it pays off in the narrative layer.

959
00:40:45,614 --> 00:40:47,555
So it kind of all comes together to create a message

960
00:40:47,555 --> 00:40:49,696
that I was much more comfortable with in the game.

961
00:40:49,696 --> 00:40:52,597
So at this point I had a simulation that was in line

962
00:40:52,597 --> 00:40:55,019
with the message I wanted to send.

963
00:40:55,019 --> 00:40:56,879
Players had good feedback about the status

964
00:40:56,879 --> 00:40:58,020
of these relationships.

965
00:40:58,020 --> 00:40:59,961
The story had a definable shape.

966
00:40:59,961 --> 00:41:02,482
The characters responded in ways that were believable

967
00:41:02,482 --> 00:41:03,862
in the edge cases.

968
00:41:03,862 --> 00:41:05,243
And the gameplay was mapped to this idea

969
00:41:05,243 --> 00:41:07,104
of relational effort.

970
00:41:07,104 --> 00:41:09,345
And it wasn't easy, but with careful and skillful play

971
00:41:09,345 --> 00:41:11,886
you actually could get a happy ending for every character.

972
00:41:13,238 --> 00:41:15,239
So I felt like I'd finally gotten the lights working,

973
00:41:15,239 --> 00:41:16,740
and was looking at my beautiful house,

974
00:41:16,740 --> 00:41:18,481
and felt proud of what I'd done.

975
00:41:18,481 --> 00:41:21,783
But it, of course, didn't quite work out that way.

976
00:41:21,783 --> 00:41:24,344
Because I worked so hard to hide these numbers

977
00:41:24,344 --> 00:41:25,004
from the characters.

978
00:41:25,004 --> 00:41:26,225
And I always thought that was a good idea.

979
00:41:26,225 --> 00:41:26,825
Or from players.

980
00:41:26,825 --> 00:41:28,026
I always thought that was a good idea.

981
00:41:28,026 --> 00:41:29,727
I never wanted you to be thinking of these meters

982
00:41:29,727 --> 00:41:30,347
when you're playing.

983
00:41:30,347 --> 00:41:34,249
I always wanted it to be focused on story and characters,

984
00:41:34,249 --> 00:41:36,010
and not the simulation.

985
00:41:36,010 --> 00:41:38,212
And that ended up working against me in this case.

986
00:41:38,212 --> 00:41:39,392
So let's look at an example.

987
00:41:40,133 --> 00:41:44,898
So here's a play through where so far the player has chosen the novel twice

988
00:41:44,898 --> 00:41:47,500
and he's done a compromise once for Tommy and once for Linda.

989
00:41:47,500 --> 00:41:49,822
So he's got, you know, up to 17 points in this system.

990
00:41:49,822 --> 00:41:53,024
So, so far, so good. He's, he's playing it the right way.

991
00:41:53,024 --> 00:41:55,507
But what if he chooses the novel again?

992
00:41:57,208 --> 00:41:58,948
or you can't go higher than nine,

993
00:41:58,948 --> 00:42:00,729
but the marriage and parenthood scores

994
00:42:00,729 --> 00:42:02,589
are still subject to the same rules.

995
00:42:02,589 --> 00:42:04,209
So all of a sudden, the player has done

996
00:42:04,209 --> 00:42:06,390
what they perceive to be the right thing,

997
00:42:06,390 --> 00:42:07,870
and what the game is saying is the right thing,

998
00:42:07,870 --> 00:42:10,731
and yet you've actually lost a point from the system.

999
00:42:10,731 --> 00:42:13,032
And the problem is that even players

1000
00:42:13,032 --> 00:42:14,932
who are engaging with the game and playing the right way

1001
00:42:14,932 --> 00:42:16,892
and trying to make the good choices,

1002
00:42:16,892 --> 00:42:18,553
and even when the onscreen feedback was saying

1003
00:42:18,553 --> 00:42:20,373
they were making the right choices,

1004
00:42:20,373 --> 00:42:22,774
they were under the hood sort of getting failed

1005
00:42:22,774 --> 00:42:24,874
by the system itself because there wasn't enough

1006
00:42:24,874 --> 00:42:26,415
dynamic range in the system.

1007
00:42:26,915 --> 00:42:30,818
And even when players became aware of how the system worked at a high level

1008
00:42:30,818 --> 00:42:32,880
and really tried to game it, you know, people were like,

1009
00:42:32,880 --> 00:42:35,162
okay, I'll do Dan, Linda, Tommy. Dan, Linda, Tommy.

1010
00:42:35,162 --> 00:42:37,264
And just try to cycle through the game

1011
00:42:37,264 --> 00:42:39,966
and try to keep everything in balance.

1012
00:42:39,966 --> 00:42:41,687
I kind of got sort of caught off guard

1013
00:42:41,687 --> 00:42:44,570
by the fact that people got so emotionally wrapped up

1014
00:42:44,570 --> 00:42:47,272
in the content of the game that they'd say,

1015
00:42:47,272 --> 00:42:48,553
okay, cool, it's Tommy's chapter.

1016
00:42:48,553 --> 00:42:50,094
And they get ready to go, and they're like, oh, man.

1017
00:42:51,252 --> 00:42:52,273
I gotta choose Linda here.

1018
00:42:52,273 --> 00:42:53,693
They're like, oh, I mean, because the actual

1019
00:42:53,693 --> 00:42:54,954
just subject matter of the chapter

1020
00:42:54,954 --> 00:42:56,295
would make them feel like, oh my God,

1021
00:42:56,295 --> 00:42:58,176
I can't not take her side, even though I know

1022
00:42:58,176 --> 00:42:59,296
I'm supposed to give this one to Tommy.

1023
00:42:59,296 --> 00:43:03,638
And so they would end up, sometimes this would lead them

1024
00:43:03,638 --> 00:43:05,979
to bump into the ceiling, and without knowing it,

1025
00:43:05,979 --> 00:43:07,580
basically take points out of the system

1026
00:43:07,580 --> 00:43:09,801
and make things worse, because in a weird way,

1027
00:43:09,801 --> 00:43:11,962
it was bad that they were connecting emotionally

1028
00:43:11,962 --> 00:43:15,264
with the material, from a purely numbers standpoint,

1029
00:43:15,264 --> 00:43:15,764
I guess, so.

1030
00:43:16,585 --> 00:43:19,647
If you did this only twice in the game,

1031
00:43:19,647 --> 00:43:21,268
you lost four points from the system.

1032
00:43:21,268 --> 00:43:23,289
Because every time you hit the ceiling, you lose a point,

1033
00:43:23,289 --> 00:43:25,751
but then it takes another chapter to get that point back.

1034
00:43:25,751 --> 00:43:27,091
So if you do that twice,

1035
00:43:27,091 --> 00:43:28,512
you can only get up to 20 instead of 24.

1036
00:43:28,512 --> 00:43:31,995
And if you see there, with only 20 points in the system,

1037
00:43:31,995 --> 00:43:34,136
one character still gets a bad ending.

1038
00:43:34,136 --> 00:43:36,117
So this is a huge bummer,

1039
00:43:36,117 --> 00:43:38,639
because players often played the game well,

1040
00:43:38,639 --> 00:43:40,200
and yet they still ended up with one character

1041
00:43:40,200 --> 00:43:43,562
who had an unhappy ending, which was never my intent.

1042
00:43:43,562 --> 00:43:44,723
And in fact,

1043
00:43:45,947 --> 00:43:50,131
The game had kind of gotten back to where I was sending this unintentional message

1044
00:43:50,131 --> 00:43:56,457
that is not what I wanted to say about life, but unfortunately, this is one that I did not realize until after the game was released.

1045
00:43:56,457 --> 00:43:59,020
So I started seeing reviews and getting feedback from players saying that

1046
00:43:59,020 --> 00:44:03,324
there's no way to have a happy ending, someone's always let down, it's this depressing thing,

1047
00:44:03,324 --> 00:44:06,266
and I was confused. I was like, what are you talking about? You can make everybody happy.

1048
00:44:06,266 --> 00:44:10,771
I built the game that way. It's supposed to work that way. Why are you guys playing it wrong?

1049
00:44:11,071 --> 00:44:12,752
Which of course is idiotic on my part.

1050
00:44:12,752 --> 00:44:15,473
But in the end I realized I had left this glitch,

1051
00:44:15,473 --> 00:44:16,614
essentially a glitch in the system,

1052
00:44:16,614 --> 00:44:18,995
that made it possible to play the game well,

1053
00:44:18,995 --> 00:44:21,457
and yet have the game send the exact message

1054
00:44:21,457 --> 00:44:22,717
that I had tried to avoid.

1055
00:44:22,717 --> 00:44:23,798
And the hell of it is,

1056
00:44:23,798 --> 00:44:25,699
it wouldn't have even been that hard to fix.

1057
00:44:25,699 --> 00:44:27,280
Like it's, it's a very small thing,

1058
00:44:27,280 --> 00:44:29,581
but I just didn't understand the scope of the problem

1059
00:44:29,581 --> 00:44:30,702
until after it was released.

1060
00:44:30,702 --> 00:44:32,383
Like I sort of, I knew it could happen,

1061
00:44:32,383 --> 00:44:33,523
but I was like, oh yeah, but...

1062
00:44:33,703 --> 00:44:35,485
if you just get to nine, just don't pick that one again.

1063
00:44:35,485 --> 00:44:38,087
But then, that was because I was sitting here thinking

1064
00:44:38,087 --> 00:44:40,049
as the person who understands the system,

1065
00:44:40,049 --> 00:44:42,952
as opposed to a player who none of this is exposed to.

1066
00:44:42,952 --> 00:44:45,754
And I had sort of assumed a level of familiarity

1067
00:44:45,754 --> 00:44:48,016
that wasn't actually realistic.

1068
00:44:48,712 --> 00:44:49,892
That said, I can rationalize this away.

1069
00:44:49,892 --> 00:44:55,096
You can argue that that scoring system is actually partially fair, because to get there

1070
00:44:55,096 --> 00:44:58,418
you do have to really zero in on one of those relationships for like three chapters in a

1071
00:44:58,418 --> 00:44:58,578
row.

1072
00:44:58,578 --> 00:45:02,641
And if you do that, you are kind of neglecting the other people, and maybe you do get what

1073
00:45:02,641 --> 00:45:03,721
you asked for.

1074
00:45:03,721 --> 00:45:07,544
And so maybe that mitigates some of the problem, even though ultimately I do think that's still

1075
00:45:07,544 --> 00:45:08,084
a flaw in the game.

1076
00:45:08,084 --> 00:45:13,788
So in the end, the mistake there was just assuming that players had knowledge of the

1077
00:45:13,788 --> 00:45:17,610
systems that they didn't, and that they understood it to agree that they had no way of understanding

1078
00:45:17,610 --> 00:45:17,650
it.

1079
00:45:18,665 --> 00:45:22,287
bad on my part. And so, despite, you know, going

1080
00:45:22,287 --> 00:45:24,948
to great lengths to, to hide the scoring and

1081
00:45:24,948 --> 00:45:28,190
making it analog, that actually worked against me.

1082
00:45:28,190 --> 00:45:32,093
So that's a bummer. But, frankly, the more I

1083
00:45:32,093 --> 00:45:34,014
think about it, cause this is something that really

1084
00:45:34,014 --> 00:45:37,796
I've only been like experienced with the game since

1085
00:45:37,796 --> 00:45:38,697
it came out. I think if given the choice,

1086
00:45:38,697 --> 00:45:41,138
I would rather err on the side of having

1087
00:45:41,138 --> 00:45:43,119
choices be a little more difficult and having the

1088
00:45:43,119 --> 00:45:45,601
consequences being a little harsher.

1089
00:45:45,961 --> 00:45:49,984
Because frankly, I don't want it to be too easy to get a happy ending.

1090
00:45:49,984 --> 00:45:53,988
Because meaningful choices are the root of memorable experiences for the players.

1091
00:45:53,988 --> 00:45:57,070
And if they're a little too harsh, that, you know, I wish they weren't like that.

1092
00:45:57,070 --> 00:45:59,772
But that might make players think more about those choices,

1093
00:45:59,772 --> 00:46:03,475
and put a little more thought into it, and connect with it a little more.

1094
00:46:03,475 --> 00:46:04,716
And in life, it's hard to have it all.

1095
00:46:04,716 --> 00:46:08,239
And sometimes there is a system that works against you in ways that you don't even know.

1096
00:46:08,239 --> 00:46:12,522
So I've kind of halfway talked myself into this bug

1097
00:46:12,522 --> 00:46:14,984
being a subconsciously intentional feature and not a bug.

1098
00:46:15,465 --> 00:46:16,625
But it's a book.

1099
00:46:16,625 --> 00:46:20,126
But the more I tell myself that, the more I'll say it

1100
00:46:20,126 --> 00:46:21,686
was my authorial intent.

1101
00:46:21,686 --> 00:46:24,027
And you guys just don't understand my

1102
00:46:24,027 --> 00:46:26,507
brilliance and all that.

1103
00:46:26,507 --> 00:46:30,048
So anyway, I want to finish with a couple other lessons

1104
00:46:30,048 --> 00:46:32,709
and conclusions that I got from working on the game.

1105
00:46:32,709 --> 00:46:36,429
Creating a dynamic narrative is really, really, really hard.

1106
00:46:36,429 --> 00:46:38,710
I thought it would be hard when I set out, and it was

1107
00:46:38,710 --> 00:46:39,890
even harder than I expected.

1108
00:46:40,734 --> 00:46:46,380
Because it's really, really difficult to take away some fundamental assumptions about how game stories are authored,

1109
00:46:46,380 --> 00:46:51,666
and then work backwards so that the player still perceives it as the same type of narrative they're used to getting.

1110
00:46:51,666 --> 00:46:55,851
Because players don't give a crap how it works. They just want to have a good story and a good experience.

1111
00:46:55,851 --> 00:46:58,874
So it's on you to try to make as much of that happen as possible.

1112
00:46:59,315 --> 00:47:03,159
while still doing all your weird aspirational stuff under the hood to try to make a different

1113
00:47:03,159 --> 00:47:07,365
type of game. So it was very, very difficult. And I felt like I was constantly battling uphill to

1114
00:47:07,365 --> 00:47:12,451
take these under the hood simulations and really feed them back to the player and

1115
00:47:12,451 --> 00:47:17,037
construct a story out of it instead of it just being this idea of system soup.

1116
00:47:17,457 --> 00:47:19,460
It also doesn't save much work.

1117
00:47:19,460 --> 00:47:21,342
I had this naive idea when I started

1118
00:47:21,342 --> 00:47:24,306
that since it was rooted in simulation character relationships,

1119
00:47:24,306 --> 00:47:27,330
there would actually be less work than authoring, you know,

1120
00:47:27,330 --> 00:47:29,894
even a branching story, even a linear story,

1121
00:47:29,894 --> 00:47:31,836
because I was like, well, you know, I can take a lot of,

1122
00:47:31,836 --> 00:47:33,519
you know, advantages of, you know,

1123
00:47:33,519 --> 00:47:35,341
procedural stuff and systemic stuff, but...

1124
00:47:36,068 --> 00:47:38,749
The way that I built my story, I had to account

1125
00:47:38,749 --> 00:47:40,770
for all of the outcomes in all of the chapters.

1126
00:47:40,770 --> 00:47:43,390
So every chapter, I had to have Dan's good, middle,

1127
00:47:43,390 --> 00:47:46,371
and bad outcome, and Linda's good, middle, and bad,

1128
00:47:46,371 --> 00:47:47,551
and Tommy's good, middle, and bad.

1129
00:47:47,551 --> 00:47:50,052
And with Linda and Tommy, when they speak up for each other,

1130
00:47:50,052 --> 00:47:51,572
I actually had to have their conditional ones, too.

1131
00:47:51,572 --> 00:47:53,232
So they had five outcomes per chapter.

1132
00:47:53,232 --> 00:47:55,813
So I had to build 13 outcomes for nine chapters.

1133
00:47:55,813 --> 00:47:59,734
And so it didn't really actually save any amount of time.

1134
00:47:59,734 --> 00:48:01,914
And I bet it was a wash compared to doing this

1135
00:48:01,914 --> 00:48:03,295
as a traditional branching story.

1136
00:48:03,295 --> 00:48:05,835
I do think it has other advantages.

1137
00:48:05,835 --> 00:48:06,015
But.

1138
00:48:06,656 --> 00:48:09,959
But it definitely didn't save me the kind of

1139
00:48:09,959 --> 00:48:11,401
work that I, that I thought it did.

1140
00:48:11,401 --> 00:48:13,844
And this last one's important too.

1141
00:48:13,844 --> 00:48:16,807
The feedback burden is really, really, really high with

1142
00:48:16,807 --> 00:48:17,828
this kind of thing.

1143
00:48:19,669 --> 00:48:21,752
When a game has a non-standard narrative loop,

1144
00:48:21,752 --> 00:48:23,574
and when the story reacts to player choices

1145
00:48:23,574 --> 00:48:24,815
based on these personal values,

1146
00:48:24,815 --> 00:48:26,898
you have to use every possible channel

1147
00:48:26,898 --> 00:48:28,400
to tell the player what's going on.

1148
00:48:28,400 --> 00:48:30,102
This was a battle that I had

1149
00:48:30,102 --> 00:48:32,244
constantly throughout development,

1150
00:48:32,244 --> 00:48:34,247
and every build, you know, the first build I sent out,

1151
00:48:34,247 --> 00:48:35,929
people were like, I literally don't know what's happening.

1152
00:48:35,929 --> 00:48:37,431
I do not know what's going on with this game.

1153
00:48:37,431 --> 00:48:38,071
I can't figure it out.

1154
00:48:38,071 --> 00:48:39,032
It's a confusing mess.

1155
00:48:39,513 --> 00:48:45,716
And so I added one set of things, and the next set of things, and I added the act breaks, and then I added, um, memory stuff.

1156
00:48:45,716 --> 00:48:53,259
And then, like, I, I constantly was sort of backfilling to try to create enough feedback so players would even just literally understand the game itself.

1157
00:48:53,259 --> 00:48:57,521
Um, you know, when, when you're doing a, an authored plot, even a branching one...

1158
00:48:58,029 --> 00:48:59,770
you can control what the player sees and when.

1159
00:48:59,770 --> 00:49:01,850
You can guarantee they're gonna get to this point

1160
00:49:01,850 --> 00:49:03,411
and get this piece of narrative information.

1161
00:49:03,411 --> 00:49:06,572
But when you're trying to build this out of a simulation

1162
00:49:06,572 --> 00:49:07,432
like I was trying to do,

1163
00:49:07,432 --> 00:49:09,392
you can't take a lot of stuff for granted

1164
00:49:09,392 --> 00:49:11,073
and you can't really funnel the player too much.

1165
00:49:11,073 --> 00:49:13,954
So you have to just basically take advantage

1166
00:49:13,954 --> 00:49:16,374
of every channel you can to try to get your point

1167
00:49:16,374 --> 00:49:17,475
across to the player.

1168
00:49:17,475 --> 00:49:19,315
And you basically have to scrap and claw

1169
00:49:19,315 --> 00:49:21,336
for every piece of feedback that you can find.

1170
00:49:21,336 --> 00:49:23,156
So I tried to litter it all over the game

1171
00:49:23,156 --> 00:49:25,277
and it took a lot of work to get there.

1172
00:49:26,420 --> 00:49:28,984
But the last point is, I think it was all worth it.

1173
00:49:28,984 --> 00:49:30,867
I don't regret building the game this way.

1174
00:49:30,867 --> 00:49:33,891
Players got really invested with the subject matter,

1175
00:49:33,891 --> 00:49:37,036
and they had really, really personal experiences with it.

1176
00:49:37,780 --> 00:49:40,901
I know it sounds like a cliche, but a lot of game reviewers

1177
00:49:40,901 --> 00:49:44,742
talk about how the game made them cry multiple times.

1178
00:49:44,742 --> 00:49:46,862
I get emails from players sharing

1179
00:49:46,862 --> 00:49:49,763
their personal experiences with the game and people

1180
00:49:49,763 --> 00:49:52,803
who have reconciled with their partners over playing the game

1181
00:49:52,803 --> 00:49:54,984
and making them think about how they treat other people.

1182
00:49:54,984 --> 00:49:57,844
I've had people reconsider how they interact with their families

1183
00:49:57,844 --> 00:50:00,365
and change their behavior based on seeing

1184
00:50:00,365 --> 00:50:02,785
how their choices affect others.

1185
00:50:03,426 --> 00:50:04,967
And so that really means a lot to me.

1186
00:50:04,967 --> 00:50:07,710
And I think that those emotional responses from people

1187
00:50:07,710 --> 00:50:10,232
really come from the fact that when you give players

1188
00:50:10,232 --> 00:50:12,354
the ability to put their own values and choices

1189
00:50:12,354 --> 00:50:14,897
into a story in a real way, I think they recognize that

1190
00:50:14,897 --> 00:50:16,518
and they value it and they understand it.

1191
00:50:16,518 --> 00:50:19,581
And when they get that kind of personal experience,

1192
00:50:19,581 --> 00:50:20,962
they know it's not something that can come

1193
00:50:20,962 --> 00:50:21,703
from another medium.

1194
00:50:21,703 --> 00:50:23,325
And that really means a lot to players.

1195
00:50:23,325 --> 00:50:24,706
And so I think this is really something

1196
00:50:24,706 --> 00:50:25,407
that's worth pursuing.

1197
00:50:26,247 --> 00:50:29,568
And finally, I just think it's important to take risks

1198
00:50:29,568 --> 00:50:31,109
and try to find new ways of doing things.

1199
00:50:31,109 --> 00:50:33,390
Like, my game certainly is not perfect,

1200
00:50:33,390 --> 00:50:37,471
but my hope is that people will take some inspiration from it

1201
00:50:37,471 --> 00:50:41,533
and learn maybe, even if you just learned one thing from it,

1202
00:50:41,533 --> 00:50:44,234
it would be cool, you know, to see people take some of this stuff further

1203
00:50:44,234 --> 00:50:47,855
and continue to take games into places that only games can go,

1204
00:50:47,855 --> 00:50:49,255
because it's important to take risks,

1205
00:50:49,255 --> 00:50:51,716
even if they don't work out the way you thought.

1206
00:50:51,716 --> 00:50:52,677
You can still learn a lot,

1207
00:50:52,677 --> 00:50:55,618
and I learned a lot over making, over the course of this game.

1208
00:50:55,618 --> 00:50:55,658
So...

1209
00:50:56,178 --> 00:50:57,540
You know, in the end, I'm glad I made it,

1210
00:50:57,540 --> 00:50:59,541
and I'm very proud of it, and I hope that, uh,

1211
00:50:59,541 --> 00:51:02,404
what I learned in making it will be helpful to you all as well.

1212
00:51:02,404 --> 00:51:03,405
So thank you very much. -♪

1213
00:51:03,405 --> 00:51:13,274
And I don't kno-

1214
00:51:13,274 --> 00:51:14,715
I don't know if we have time for Q&A

1215
00:51:14,715 --> 00:51:17,457
or if anybody has questions, but it's, you know, five o'-

1216
00:51:17,457 --> 00:51:19,819
Oh, look. Who are you now?

1217
00:51:19,819 --> 00:51:20,780
My name's Clint.

1218
00:51:21,180 --> 00:51:30,406
I have one question. With regards to the compromise system, to build on your example, you know,

1219
00:51:30,406 --> 00:51:34,409
Chevy Chase has to like, I forget his name in the movies, but whatever, he has to like

1220
00:51:34,409 --> 00:51:39,753
learn to better empathize with the people in his family and learn to see why they're

1221
00:51:39,753 --> 00:51:45,016
upset or why they're not getting along with each other and he has to improve himself by

1222
00:51:45,016 --> 00:51:48,199
examining himself and changing his behavior.

1223
00:51:49,115 --> 00:51:53,516
working harder I think as you put it in order to fix those things and get a happy outcome.

1224
00:51:53,516 --> 00:52:02,719
In the novelist, Dan doesn't go through that process. You go through that process as a player

1225
00:52:02,719 --> 00:52:08,040
but then the way you work harder is instead of by trying to be more empathetic or trying to

